# `cdf_discovery` governance UI — language files and new UI strings

When you add or change anything that surfaces **user-visible text** in the governance UI (labels, buttons, tabs, hints, errors, status messages, placeholders, aria text, etc.), **update internationalization in the same change**, not only the component.

## What to update

1. **`ui/src/i18n/types.ts`**
   - Add a new literal to the `MessageKey` union (use dotted keys consistent with existing entries, e.g. `governance.*`, `dimensions.*`).
   - If you introduce a **new locale**, extend the `Locale` union here.

2. **Every locale message file** — keep them aligned (same set as `cdf_discovery_aliasing`):
   - `ui/src/i18n/en.ts`, `ar.ts`, `de.ts`, `es.ts`, `fr.ts`, `nb.ts`, `pt.ts`, `hi.ts`, `ja.ts`, `zh.ts`  
   Each file exports a `Messages` object: **every `MessageKey` must have a string in every locale.**

3. **`ui/src/i18n/index.ts`** (only when adding or removing a **locale**)
   - Import/export the new locale module.
   - Add it to `LOCALES` and to `translations`.
   - Ensure `translations` satisfies `Record<Locale, Messages>`.

## Conventions

- Prefer **`t("some.key")`** (via `createTranslator`) for any string the user sees; avoid hard-coded English in components except dev-only diagnostics.
- Preserve **`{placeholder}`** names and count across locales when English uses interpolation; translations must supply the same placeholders.
- For non-English files, provide a proper translation when you can; if you must ship a partial change, mirror the English string **only as a temporary measure** and keep keys identical across files so TypeScript stays satisfied.

## Quick check

After edits, `MessageKey`, `Messages`, and all locale objects should agree so **`ui/src/i18n/types.ts` and the locale `.ts` files compile** with no missing keys.
